Life in Water7
Let's KnowLet's KnowMany beautiful plants, grasses and animals are found in water. Together they 
form an amazing aquatic life. Let's read about some of them.
Plants in WaterPlants that are found in water are called aquatic plants. On the basis of how they 
grow, they are divided into three groups.
1. 
Free-floating plants– Plants like duckweed, water hyacinth, water lettuce, 
water chestnut etc. that float on the surface of water are called free floating 
plants. The roots of these plants are poorly developed or even absent. The 
body of these plants is light and spongy so that they can float freely on the 
surface of water.
2. 
Submerged (Underwater) plants– Plants like hydrilla, tape grass, pondweed 
etc. remain completely immersed in water. The roots of these plants are fixed 
to the waterbed. The leaves of these plants are narrow with no pores. They 
Environmental Studies-550Unit–II : The Living World

absorb water, nutrients and dissolved gas directly from water through their 
whole body surface. They help in keeping the water clean by absorbing 
carbon dioxide breathed out by 
 living in water.
the animals3. 
Fixed-floating plants– Floating plants whose roots are fixed to the waterbed 
are called 'Fixed-floating plants' e.g. lotus, water lily etc. Such plants have 
long hollow stems which reach the surface of water and keep the leaves and 
flowers afloat. Their leaves are waxy and have stomata on the upper side.
Animals in WaterAnimals that live in or on the surface of water are called aquatic animals. Water is 
home to a huge variety of aquatic animals such as different species of fish, water 
mammals, shelled animals, water birds, insects etc.
Fish– Fish have a streamlined body and fins that help them swim in water. They 
breathe through gills. Goldfish, catfish, carp, trout, seahorse etc. are different 
types of fish found in water.
Environmental Studies-551

Water mammals– Dolphins and whales are mammals that live in water. They give 
birth to young ones and breathe with lungs. They keep coming to the surface of 
water to breathe in fresh air. They also have fins and streamlined bodies like fish, 
which help them swim.
Water birds– Water birds such 
as ducks or heron breathe 
through lungs and tiny nostrils 
located at the top of their 
beaks. Ducks have webbed 
feet which help them to swim 
while herons have long and slim legs that help them to stand in water.
Amphibians– Amphibians are 
animals like toads and frogs 
that can live both on land and 
in water. When they are in 
water, they breathe through 
their moist skin and when on 
land, they use their lungs for breathing. They lay eggs in water and the young ones 
live and grow in water till they become adult.
Mosquitoes– Mosquitoes do not live in water but they lay eggs in stagnant water. A 
mosquito is a parasitic insect that feeds on animals and human blood. Mosquitoes 
spread many dangerous diseases like malaria, dengue, chickengunia etc. 
Shelled animals– Turtles, 
crabs, snails, prawns and 
lobsters are also aquatic 
animals. They have a hard 
protective shell as an outer 
covering. These animals have 
paddle-like flippers and special limbs that help them to walk across the bottom of 
the water bodies. They breathe through gills.

Prevention– It is important to prevent the outbreak of malaria and dengue. Some 
tips on how this can be done are–
! 
Do not let water collect in or around your house.
! 
Change the water in water coolers every 2-3 days. 
! 
Clean water pots and tanks regularly.
! 
Use mosquito nets, coils, mats etc. at night.
! 
Spray kerosene oil on stagnant water.
! 
Keep your surroundings clean.
! 
Spray DDT around the area where mosquitoes could breed.
! 
Wear clothes that cover your arms and legs.
Environmental Studies-553Symptoms of Malaria and DengueMalaria– Chills, fever and sweating. Nausea and headache also occur with fever.
Dengue – High fever, severe headache, muscles and joint pains, vomiting, eye pain 
and rashes.

Preservation of FoodUnit–III : Our Needs8
How Does Food Get SpoiltSome very tiny living beings called micro-organism or microbes are always present 
in our environment. Microbes are so small that they can not be seen with our 
naked eyes. They can be seen only through microscope. 
Food is very important for our survival. Some food items like fruits, bread, 
vegetables, etc. get spoiled in a short span of time if not kept in the 
refrigerator. Such food items are called perishable foods. Whereas foods like 
pulses, grains, sugar, honey etc. can be used over a long time and do not 
require refrigeration. They are called non perishable or imperishable foods.
From the pictures given below, tick (3) the foods that can be used for a 
long time and do not require refrigeration.
Let's KnowLet's KnowEnvironmental Studies-556

These microbes grow rapidly in warm air and 
humid conditions. If the cooked food, milk and 
other perishable foods are left lying around for a 
long time, microbes begin to grow on or in the 
food, leading to the spoiling of food. Spoiled 
food may have a foul smell, change in colour, 
sticky feel and a sour taste. Eating spoiled food 
can make us sick. It can also lead to a serious 
condition called food poisoning which often 
includes upset stomach, diarrhoea and vomiting.

ActivityActivityPreventing SpoilageWe can follow a few simple practices to prevent spoilage of food.
! Perishable foods like milk, fruits and vegetables must be kept in the fridge.
! Food should preferably be prepared fresh, in required quantity and 
consumed as soon as possible.
! Foods like spices, cereals, biscuits and other snacks should be kept in air tight 
containers.
! Shelves and cupboards must be kept clean and dry. This will prevent spoilage 
of stored food by insects ,worms and rats.
Environmental Studies-557

Preservation of FoodIt is not always possible to eat all the food that we have bought or cooked. So, we 
need to preserve food. Food preservation is the process of treating and handling 
food to stop spoilage by microbes ( bacteria and fungi).Some methods of food 
preservation are–
1. Freezing– Bacteria and fungi can not survive in low temperature. 
So, some foods are frozen to prevent them from spoilage. Cooked 
and raw food items are stored in the refrigerator at home. Cold 
stores are used to preserve large amount of food stuff for a longer 
period of time.
2. Cooking– Heating and boiling food kills bacteria and fungi and prevent the food 
from spoiling. Milk is boiled to prevent it from getting spoilt.
3. Sunning and Drying– The water in the food 
item dries up if it is kept in the sun. Bacteria 
and fungi cannot live without water. Pulses 
can be preserved by drying them in the heat 
of the sun.
4. Pickling– Pickling is one of the traditional 
methods of preserving foods like mangoes, 
lemon ,carrots, raddish and other vegetables. 
In this method, the ingredients are dried and 
then oil ,salt and preservatives are added to it.
5. Canning and Bottling– The traditional methods 
of sun drying and pickling have changed with 
time. Now, the food stuffs are cooked and stored 
in sterilized tin containers. Fruits and vegetables 
are canned so that no air can enter and hence 
germs do not grow. Food sealed in tins, bottles, 
Environmental Studies-558

etc. can be kept at room temperature as long as they are not opened. Once they 
are opened, they should be eaten quickly or put in a refrigerator.
6. Adding preservatives– Biscuits and sweets generally contain added chemicals 
called preservatives so that they do not get spoilt. Salt, sugar, vinegar and 
certain chemicals like sodium benzoate and sodium metabisulphite are 
commonly used preservatives.
7. Packaging– Some food items such as juices are stored 
in especially made packs called tetra packs. Food is 
packed in tetra packs using nitrogen gas or by 
removing air.
8. Pasteurisation– Milk is preserved by the 
process of pasteurisation. In this process, the 
milk is heated to a set temperature for a short 
period and then suddenly cooled to a very low 
temperature to kill the germs in it. Pasteurized 
milk can be used for a few days as it does not get 
spoilt quickly.
Scarcity of FoodThere are times when availability of food is scarce. The causes of food shortage 
may be natural or man-made. The natural causes of food scarcity may be droughts, 
floods or diseases to the crops.
The man made causes of food scarcity are : black- marketing and illegal hoarding . 
At times when there is a shortage of food supply, some shopkeepers hold food 
items and later sell them at higher prices.
Famine in BengalWhen there is a severe shortage of food, it is called a famine. The Bengal famine of 
1943 occured during World War II. It took place because the British burnt the rice 
fields in Bengal. About three million people died of starvation and malnutrition in 
Bengal due to this famine. 
Environmental Studies-559

Food For AllMillions of people starve everyday because they do not get anything to eat. So, we 
should try not to waste any food. To stop the wastage, we should take following 
steps–
! Do not buy and cook food in excess.
! Do not leave food in plate, take according to your appetite.
! Store and preserve the food properly.
! If the food is left over, share it with the poor and needy people.

– 
Very tiny organisms such as bacteria ,virus and fungus.
Ÿ Ingredient 
– 
any of the food or substances that are combined to make a

Key termsKey termsKey terms
Ÿ Germs(microbes)grow on food that is kept in open for long hours.
Ÿ Microbes need air ,water and warmth to grow. 
Ÿ Food can be preserved so that it lasts longer and can be used later.
Ÿ Perishable food should be kept in the refrigerator and rest in air tight containers.
Ÿ Freezing, drying, canning, boiling, pickling, etc are some methods of food 
preservation.
Ÿ Pasteurization is a special technique to preserve milk. 
Ÿ Everybody needs food to survive so it should not be wasted.
